1507   ///
1508   /// This method contains the mechanics of fusing two loops, represented by \p
1509   /// FC0 and \p FC1. It is assumed that \p FC0 dominates \p FC1 and \p FC1
1510   /// postdominates \p FC0 (making them control flow equivalent). It also
1511   /// assumes that the other conditions for fusion have been met: adjacent,
1512   /// identical trip counts, and no negative distance dependencies exist that
1513   /// would prevent fusion. Thus, there is no checking for these conditions in
1514   /// this method.
1515   ///
1516   /// Fusion is performed by rewiring the CFG to update successor blocks of the
1517   /// components of tho loop. Specifically, the following changes are done:
1518   ///
1519   ///   1. The preheader of \p FC1 is removed as it is no longer necessary
1520   ///   (because it is currently only a single statement block).
1521   ///   2. The latch of \p FC0 is modified to jump to the header of \p FC1.
1522   ///   3. The latch of \p FC1 i modified to jump to the header of \p FC0.
1523   ///   4. All blocks from \p FC1 are removed from FC1 and added to FC0.
1524   ///
1525   /// All of these modifications are done with dominator tree updates, thus
1526   /// keeping the dominator (and post dominator) information up-to-date.
1527   ///
1528   /// This can be improved in the future by actually merging blocks during
1529   /// fusion. For example, the preheader of \p FC1 can be merged with the
1530   /// preheader of \p FC0. This would allow loops with more than a single
1531   /// statement in the preheader to be fused. Similarly, the latch blocks of the
1532   /// two loops could also be fused into a single block. This will require
1533   /// analysis to prove it is safe to move the contents of the block past
1534   /// existing code, which currently has not been implemented.
